WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:18.320
 Ultra-fast computers and advanced mathematical formulas ... 

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:23.120
 have far surpassed humans in stock trading. 

00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:27.560
 Some algorithms seem to be alive. 

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:32.040
 Algorithms are quietly waiting for your actions at Apple ... 

00:00:32.160 --> 00:00:35.720
 or your pension money is on the market. 

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:40.440
 The only ones who fully understand this system are its architects: 

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:46.640
 algorithm developers. Haim Bodek is one of them. 

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:51.520
 After discovering strange misdeeds, he embarked on a crusade ... 

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:55.280
 against this complex system. 

00:00:55.400 --> 00:01:00.360
 This goes directly against Wall Street's tacit silence law ... 

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:04.880
 and its confidentiality. Here's what to expect. 

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.600
 It's like a rule: never accuse others, the market, traders ... 

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:13.440
 it's always your fault, your code is wrong. 

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:17.680
 On Wall Street, you are necessarily scammed unless you are the scammer. 

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:21.840
 On Wall Street, there is a culture of confidentiality. 

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:24.840
 It doesn't happen, going to the SEC. 

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:27.040
 Welcome to Backlight. 

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:32.360
 You will discover the smallest corners of our financial markets. 

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:40.520
 It is played to the nearest penny, for an action. 

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:42.600
 That's all. 

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:49.360
 When only one &lt;i&gt; tick &lt;/i&gt;, the quotation scale, or a price changes ... 

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:51.400
 this is where the game starts. 

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:58.880
 When this tick varies, the world is divided between the winners ... 

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:00.400
 and the losers. 

00:02:08.760 --> 00:02:11.760
 The machine behind the major financial markets ... 

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:14.040
 made of mathematical models ... 

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:18.560
 data centers and kilometers of fiber optic cables ... 

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:24.480
 is camouflaged by technological complexity and confidentiality. 

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:30.040
 The creators of this financial system are new employees of Wall Street: 

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:31.240
 quants ... 

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:33.640
 mathematicians and physicists ... 

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:37.000
 responsible for a technological revolution. 

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:40.240
 Haim Bodek is a quant. 

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:44.280
 Specialized in artificial intelligence, he worked for Hull Trading ... 

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:46.080
 and Goldman Sachs. 

00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:51.280
 He knows the system from the inside, he participated in its creation. 

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:56.880
 One day, I was called and advised to contact Haim Bodek ... 

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.200
 because he had information on high frequency trading ... 

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:05.280
 a subject that we dealt with in the "Battle of the Quants". So I called him. 

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:13.400
 Listening to Haim Bodek speak was like opening Pandora's box. 

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:17.920
 He entered the system to gain access to a series of files ... 

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:23.920
 containing information that is incredible, according to the public. 

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:30.880
 No one was talking about types of orders before Haim landed. 

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:34.960
 I heard what Haim was talking about: 

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:40.160
 order types which, if used properly ... 

00:03:40.280 --> 00:03:42.600
 can guarantee profit. 

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:49.480
 Several people in the audience knew that, they cowered ... 

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:53.160
 they wondered who he was, and why he was revealing it all ... 

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:57.760
 why he wasted our opportunity ... 

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:01.160
 to generate income on the financial market. 

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:07.440
 There were quite a few Russians. 

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:12.520
 One of them came to me and said to me: 

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:16.120
 "I know what you are doing. I am with you ... 

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:19.080
 "if you ever need help, someone ... 

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:23.440
 "I have contacts." 

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:26.880
 I said to him, "Am I at a conference as for?" 

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.240
 And these are just the reactions of others. I said to myself : 

00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:35.120
 "Look, it's just geeks who did this ... 

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:40.200
 "I don't think I'm going against the crowd, or anything like that." 

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:48.080
 2011, Bodek's high frequency trading business, Trading Machines ... 

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:49.520
 went bankrupt. 

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:53.200
 According to Bodek, it's because of a wrong type of order ... 

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:57.720
 or the way he told the Stock Exchange to execute his order. 

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:01.080
 This is not the installation I had before. 

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:07.160
 But hey, it will be fine. 

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:11.080
 When we launched Trading Machines ... 

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.120
 we knew which machines were slower ... 

00:05:14.240 --> 00:05:18.720
 we knew which companies were slower than us ... 

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:21.800
 and which were faster than us ... 

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:24.520
 because we have negotiated with these companies. 

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:27.920
 Were you as fast as the others? 

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:31.440
 No, we were faster than them. 

00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:43.280
 Take a second ... 

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:47.080
 it looks like it's a lifetime of transactions ... 

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:50.000
 between these algorithms that we don't even see. 

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:56.280
 It was Bartt C. Kellerman who invited Haim Bodek to tell his story ... 

00:05:56.400 --> 00:06:00.520
 at the "Battle of the Quants", a seminar during which analysts discuss ... 

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:04.080
 high frequency trading, among others. 

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:09.400
 When you buy a stock, you buy it at a price ... 

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:12.200
 and the next person who buys it has to pay more. 

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:16.440
 This margin is the advantage ... 

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:23.040
 which many of these THF organizations could benefit from. 

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:27.160
 These are minute quantities. 

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:33.680
 But if the action is repeated millions of times, it creates huge income. 

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:40.720
 10 years ago, these analysts created a model, used on the market ... 

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:43.080
 then they went to the beach to relax ... 

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:45.800
 and counted their money at the end of the day. 

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:51.240
 Bodek created an algorithm for Trading Machines ... 

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:53.920
 supposed to guarantee an income. 

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:59.160
 A slot machine that withstood the financial collapse of 2008. 

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:04.360
 But overnight, the algorithm stopped working. 

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:11.440
 I started to observe behaviors on certain exchanges ... 

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:15.160
 who were strange. 

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:18.520
 This algorithm did not allow transactions ... 

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:21.600
 even if it varied the price ... 

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:24.880
 no one was trading the stocks. 

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.040
 I go back and look for the code that has changed. 

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:30.760
 There are millions of codes. 

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:37.440
 The model I see has nothing to do with all the anomalies I have seen. 

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:42.200
 It's like a rule: never accuse others, the market, traders ... 

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:46.400
 it's always your fault, your code is wrong. 

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:51.600
 We had to wait 12 months, from that day ... 

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:57.920
 to explain it to me. And it was explained to me in person. 

00:07:58.040 --> 00:08:01.760
 That's why I haven't discovered it before. 

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:06.480
 I was there, I was looking for what mistake we had made. 

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:25.240
 I went to a seminar, organized by this scholarship ... 

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:29.600
 and I said, "I'm sorry, I have a problem." 

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:32.960
 Who were you talking to? - A type of business development ... 

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:38.600
 whose job is to improve growth on the stock market. 

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:44.120
 He explained to me that my order was systematically disadvantaged ... 

00:08:44.240 --> 00:08:47.160
 because I was using the wrong type of order. 

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:53.440
 I will not accuse the asymmetries of the financial market of what happened. 

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:57.160
 But I must say that I wasted a year of my life ... 

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:01.120
 to look for something that I could have learned by having a drink. 

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:03.080
 What was your first reaction? 

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:05.240
 I was humiliated. 

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:09.560
 I wondered how I could not have known. 

00:09:12.720 --> 00:09:15.200
 Bodek thought he understood the cogs ... 

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.640
 of our automated financial markets. 

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:20.160
 But he did not follow social codes ... 

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:24.160
 from the world of high frequency trading. 

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:29.920
 Some traders had found a way to place their order first. 

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:38.160
 Bodek started out in a pioneering company in automatic trading ... 

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:41.360
 in Chicago, at Hull Trading. 

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:49.120
 The process we used to hire people was very strict. 

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:52.640
 It was quite difficult to get a job at Hull Trading. 

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:56.920
 Blair Hull is a trading legend, a math genius. 

00:09:57.040 --> 00:10:01.720
 Hull made his first fortune at the blackjack tables in Las Vegas. 

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:05.960
 With this money, he created Hull Trading. 

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:11.800
 With his analysts, he was a forerunner of financial market automation. 

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:16.240
 In 1977, I went to the &lt;i&gt; Pacific Exchange &lt;/i&gt; ... 

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:21.480
 and I realized that all the paper on the floor didn't need to exist ... 

00:10:21.600 --> 00:10:27.440
 I thought that a good programmer could automate all of this in one or two years. 

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:32.200
 I understood well what turn things would take. 

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:34.880
 But it happened 30 years later. 

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:39.200
 Those entering Hull Trading did not want to work on Wall Street. 

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:44.440
 They entered to be surrounded by very intelligent people ... 

00:10:44.560 --> 00:10:47.400
 to solve incredible problems. 

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:52.160
 It was not seen as a job on Wall Street. 

00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:58.320
 I never would have thought of applying for an investment bank. 

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:02.320
 I'm more from the world of Google, not that of Goldman Sachs ... 

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:04.680
 even if it went well with them. 

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:17.880
 Our research on the origins of the technological revolution ... 

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:22.200
 that has affected the financial markets in recent decades ... 

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:28.320
 led us to an even more legendary trader: Thomas Peterffy. 

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:36.000
 We have everything here, the American flag, nature ... 

00:11:39.120 --> 00:11:45.680
 We are 50 minutes from New York, the weather is good, it's good. 

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:50.760
 At 21, Petterfy fled Communist Hungary. 

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:54.080
 He is one of the first to see the enormous potential ... 

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:56.240
 automatic trading. 

00:11:57.960 --> 00:12:00.800
 With his company Interactive Brokers ... 

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:04.840
 his net worth is estimated at $ 6 billion. 

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:07.840
 He receives us in his "office". 

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:12.840
 I have the first touch pad ... 

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:17.360
 that I created in 1983. 

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:24.840
 Those on the floor used it. 

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:33.200
 It was connected to a battery. 

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:39.000
 And here you could display options ... 

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:42.440
 with the strike price and the expiration date. 

00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:45.080
 There were the offers. 

00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:51.400
 Thus, the negotiators of the prosecution could know the state of the market. 

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:57.200
 And thanks to these tactile keys ... 

00:12:57.320 --> 00:12:59.680
 Is it a touch screen? - Yes. 

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:02.680
 What year? - 1983. 

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:04.640
 How were the others doing? 

00:13:04.760 --> 00:13:08.280
 The others, well, they used their brains. 

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:14.480
 Have you patented it? 

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:18.280
 No, I don't believe in patents, I think patents ... 

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:23.400
 prevent people from inventing new things. 

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:26.200
 So the other people copied you? 

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:28.840
 Of course, the others have always copied me. 

00:13:28.960 --> 00:13:31.800
 But it's nothing, it moves the world. 

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:39.560
 If there was a computer on the floor in early 1980 ... 

00:13:39.680 --> 00:13:43.680
 it was not directly connected to the price in real time. 

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:47.960
 My computer was in the office. I went up by the elevator ... 

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:52.520
 I launched my computer, went down again, executed the transactions ... 

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:56.720
 then I walked, went up, restarted the computer and went down again. 

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:59.880
 I couldn't get a price in real time. 

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.080
 The first time we had an option on the parquet ... 

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:10.080
 to enter an S&amp;P 500 price, we had a "human counter". 

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:12.720
 It was a person looking at the screen ... 

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:17.440
 and raise or lower the price to make sure it was the same. 

00:14:17.560 --> 00:14:21.320
 These were the rules that the stock market followed to ensure ... 

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:24.160
 that people weren't going to switch to automation. 

00:14:25.040 --> 00:14:32.080
 We found a way to join the cable ... 

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:35.800
 to which the keyboard was connected ... 

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:40.440
 and we used the functions of the keys on a computer. 

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:47.160
 So it was much faster, we didn't need to use the keyboard. 

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:53.120
 A NASDAQ agent came and saw it and said, "You can't do this." 

00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:56.560
 I asked him why, he replied, "Because ... 

00:14:56.680 --> 00:15:01.760
 "According to the rules, all orders must be entered using the keyboard." 

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:05.640
 So we decided to create ... 

00:15:07.720 --> 00:15:14.040
 keyboard cover with pistons, rubber fingers ... 

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:18.400
 going up and down and typing. 

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:22.960
 The only problem is that it made a lot of noise. 

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:31.120
 The next time, when the agent came back ... 

00:15:31.240 --> 00:15:34.760
 he heard this crazy noise. 

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:40.560
 Orders were flowing. And he didn't know what to do. 

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:45.880
 He stayed watching for a while, then he left. 

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.160
 We never heard from him again. 

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:55.160
 In the 90s, the establishment of Wall Street realizes ... 

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:58.480
 that it is lagging behind the technological revolution. 

00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:04.680
 Just before turning century, Blair Hull sells his business ... 

00:16:04.800 --> 00:16:06.680
 as well as its employees ... 

00:16:06.800 --> 00:16:11.600
 to investment bank Goldman Sachs for half a billion dollars. 

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:16.920
 As Hull was bought out, I was able to get involved with Goldman. 

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:20.880
 We often joked about it in Hull. 

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:26.320
 We were all given personality tests. 

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:32.480
 And the type of personality I was given ... 

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:36.080
 was, roughly, that of a mad scientist. 

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:45.280
 For about 9 months, people were worried ... 

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:48.440
 because I work in a bank. 

00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:52.400
 I spent a good part of my life, my childhood ... 

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:55.600
 surrounded by physicists in physics laboratories. 

00:16:55.720 --> 00:16:59.680
 What did your father say when you started working at the bank? 

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:03.800
 I think he was not very happy about Goldman. 

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:08.920
 In this universe, people were exceptional. 

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:16.360
 I remember that I met, during small parties, at the age of 8 years old ... 

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:19.520
 so and so who won the Nobel Prize. 

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:23.080
 My father said to me, "Come and shake their hands." 

00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:29.920
 You should know that some had created nuclear bombs. 

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:35.280
 These people believed that science would make the world a better place. 

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:38.520
 And that the way to make the world a better place ... 

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:42.600
 was to understand, create and discover. 

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:48.280
 Around the world, people watch high finance and have to think: 

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:50.800
 "Why use your intelligence like this?" 

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:56.240
 "Always make more money than others, is that genius?" 

00:17:59.360 --> 00:18:03.400
 The team of geniuses in mathematics and physics ... 

00:18:03.520 --> 00:18:09.440
 who chose to work in finance has automated 70% of transactions ... 

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:13.200
 and allowed 50% of them to happen in a few milliseconds. 

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:17.320
 We call this high frequency trading, or THF. 

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:20.000
 THF has nothing to do with the economy. 

00:18:20.120 --> 00:18:23.280
 It's about understanding how networks work ... 

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:26.200
 how they plant, how to make them plant ... 

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:31.480
 and how to plant them to your advantage without being discovered. 

